This is the sixth lesson of the series and it's the second lesson in
the second unit of the series, which is on quantum algorithms.

4
00:18.240 --> 00:26.520
In the previous lesson, we discussed the query
model of computation, and we saw that in that model, quantum algorithms can
provide a striking advantage

5
00:26.520 --> 00:33.210
over classical algorithms, including an exponential advantage in the case of Simon's problem.

6
00:33.210 --> 00:39.750
Unfortunately, the query
model doesn't really have any direct or immediate
practical relevance.

7
00:39.750 --> 00:46.440
The notion of a black box is a very useful
abstraction as it turns out, but we have some work to
do if we're going to apply

8
00:46.440 --> 00:54.090
the insights that we've
gained from the query model to a more standard computational setting where inputs are given as strings of bits

9
00:54.090 --> 00:57.510
rather than as oracles or black boxes.

10
00:57.510 --> 01:02.730
The main purpose of this lesson is to establish a foundation
from which we can do that.

11
01:02.730 --> 01:09.420
Here's an overview of the lesson. For much of the lesson, we're going to be focusing
on computational cost,

12
01:09.420 --> 01:16.050
or in other words, how difficult different
computational tasks are and how we can measure that difficulty.

13
01:16.050 --> 01:23.580
Roughly speaking, this translates to how long we have to wait
for computations to finish and ultimately which
computational problems

14
01:23.580 --> 01:27.750
we can solve and which
ones are beyond our reach.

15
01:27.750 --> 01:36.360
We're going to start with
a couple of examples. Integer factorization and computing greatest common
divisors or GCDs for short.

16
01:36.360 --> 01:45.390
These are very good examples for illustrating the
underlying principles, and they also both happen
to be highly relevant to Shor's algorithm, which we'll
discuss in the next lesson,

17
01:45.390 --> 01:49.740
so we'll effectively
get double the mileage out of these examples.

18
01:49.740 --> 01:55.140
Then we'll discuss the notion of computational costs more generally and how we can measure it.

19
01:55.140 --> 02:02.280
There are many different
ways that this can be done, but we'll focus pretty
narrowly on how we can do this with circuit models of computation,

20
02:02.280 --> 02:06.780
specifically Boolean circuits
and quantum circuits.

21
02:06.780 --> 02:12.990
The focus here will be on algorithms as opposed to computer
hardware, for instance, and we'll be more concerned

22
02:12.990 --> 02:20.730
with how the costs of
running an algorithm scale as the specific problem instances it's run on grow in size rather
than on how many seconds,

23
02:20.730 --> 02:24.390
minutes, or hours some
particular computation requires.

24
02:24.390 --> 02:30.090
The idea that motivates this point of view is that algorithms have
fundamental importance.

25
02:30.090 --> 02:37.830
To this day, we're
still running algorithms that were developed a
very, very long time ago and very naturally, they will be deployed

26
02:37.830 --> 02:45.420
against larger and
larger problem instances using faster and more reliable hardware as technology develops.

27
02:45.420 --> 02:52.620
And the way that they scale tells us a great deal
about how useful they are and how useful they'll continue to be.

28
02:52.620 --> 02:58.680
In the last section of the lesson, we'll turn to a critically important task, which is running classical computations

29
02:58.680 --> 03:06.180
on quantum computers. The reason this is important is not because we hope to replace classical computers
with quantum computers,

30
03:06.180 --> 03:12.600
which seems extremely unlikely to happen anytime soon if it ever happens, but rather because it opens up

31
03:12.600 --> 03:16.980
many interesting possibilities
for quantum algorithms.

32
03:16.980 --> 03:24.840
Specifically, once we know how to run classical computations
on quantum computers, they become available to quantum
algorithms as subroutines

33
03:24.840 --> 03:32.700
so we can effectively
leverage everything we know about classical algorithms in the pursuit of quantum computational advantages.

34
03:32.700 --> 03:37.170
The classical computers that we have today are truly marvels of technology.

35
03:37.170 --> 03:44.100
They're incredibly fast, but they're not so fast that no computational problem
is beyond their reach.

36
03:44.100 --> 03:51.720
Some computational problems
are so inherently difficult that although we do have
algorithms to solve them, no computer on the planet Earth today

37
03:51.720 --> 03:58.680
is fast enough to run these
algorithms to completion on even moderately sized inputs within the lifetime of a human

38
03:58.680 --> 04:02.460
or even within the lifetime
of the Earth itself.

39
04:02.460 --> 04:09.180
To explain further, let's take a look at the
integer factorization problem.

40
04:09.180 --> 04:18.750
The problem statement is very simple. The input to the problem is an integer N that's at least two, and the output is the
prime factorization of N,

41
04:18.750 --> 04:25.410
and what that means is a list of the prime number factors of N together with the powers that these prime numbers must be raised

42
04:25.410 --> 04:29.520
in order to get N by
multiplying them all together.

43
04:29.520 --> 04:35.670
Of course, we can always multiply the prime factors together in any order, but aside from their ordering,

44
04:35.670 --> 04:40.920
prime factorizations are always unique for every choice of N.

45
04:40.920 --> 04:47.670
That fact is called the
fundamental theorem of arithmetic, and if you're interested
in learning more about it, it's something that you can find

46
04:47.670 --> 04:53.310
at the very beginning of
many books on number theory.

47
04:53.310 --> 04:58.290
As a very simple example, here's the prime factorization
of the number 12.

48
04:58.290 --> 05:02.760
It's two to the power two
times three to the power one.

49
05:02.760 --> 05:12.720
Not surprisingly, a
computer can tell you this in the blink of an eye by simply searching
iteratively for prime factors.

50
05:12.720 --> 05:16.170
Here's another example. I won't try to read this number.

51
05:16.170 --> 05:22.500
It's about 3.4 quattuordecillion, and I have to admit that I find it strange that there's even such a name,

52
05:22.500 --> 05:29.760
but anyway, it has 46 decimal digits and here you can see
its prime factorization.

53
05:29.760 --> 05:37.860
A computer can also tell you this. I factored this number using the factoring method that's included in the symbolic mathematics
library for Python,

54
05:37.860 --> 05:44.520
and it took a few seconds, which is not a particularly long time, but there was a noticeable delay.

55
05:44.520 --> 05:50.730
And certainly the factor N method doesn't find this prime factorization by naively searching for prime factors.

56
05:50.730 --> 05:56.730
It actually uses a hybrid
of different algorithms including one called the
colored row algorithm, which is an algorithm for factoring

57
05:56.730 --> 06:04.170
that's more sophisticated than naively searching iteratively
for prime factors, and although that might seem
like a pretty large number,

58
06:04.170 --> 06:08.580
as an input to a computational problem, it isn't really all that large at all.

59
06:08.580 --> 06:12.990
It's only 46 characters.

60
06:12.990 --> 06:18.030
Here's one more example. It's a number with 309 decimal digits.

61
06:18.030 --> 06:25.560
If we write it in binary notation, it has 1,024 bits and that's
why it's called RSA1024.

62
06:25.560 --> 06:29.700
The prime factorization of this number is not currently known.

63
06:29.700 --> 06:38.040
This number comes from the
RSA factoring challenge, which was run by RSA
Laboratories from 1991 to 2007.

64
06:38.040 --> 06:46.140
They offered cash prizes
for the prime factorizations of various numbers of increasing
size, including this one, which was worth $100,000 US,

65
06:46.140 --> 06:49.200
but that prize was never collected.

66
06:49.200 --> 06:55.080
The security of the RSA
public key crypto system is based on the difficulty
of integer factorization.

67
06:55.080 --> 07:04.710
If you can factor, you
can break the system, and so the purpose of the challenge was basically to track the
state of the art in factoring.

68
07:04.710 --> 07:09.810
The bottom line is that
factoring this number is beyond our current abilities.

69
07:09.810 --> 07:16.320
As far as we know, the
problem itself is too complex for classical computers
to solve in practice.

70
07:16.320 --> 07:23.040
The largest RSA challenge number to have been factored so far, by the way, has 250 decimal digits.

71
07:23.040 --> 07:29.430
It might be a little bit hard
to read this on the screen, but here's the prime
factorization of RSA250.

72
07:29.430 --> 07:39.720
It was done in 2020 using an algorithm known as the number field sieve, and it was a collective effort involving tens of thousands
of computers around the world.

73
07:39.720 --> 07:46.860
Now, let's consider a different
computational problem, which is the problem of computing the greatest common
divisor, or GCD for short,

74
07:46.860 --> 07:51.030
of two non-negative integers.

75
07:51.030 --> 07:57.090
Here's a statement of the problem. The input consists of two
numbers this time, N and M,

76
07:57.090 --> 08:02.490
and we're gonna assume that
they aren't both equal to zero.

77
08:02.490 --> 08:11.370
The goal is to compute the
GCD of these two numbers, which is the largest integer D that evenly divides both N and M,

78
08:11.370 --> 08:17.970
and if you think about the
prime factorizations of N and M, what you'll find is that the GCD is the product of all the prime numbers

79
08:17.970 --> 08:25.020
that divide both N and M raised to the minimum of the powers that appear in the two
prime factorizations.

80
08:25.020 --> 08:31.440
So it's related to the problem
of integer factorization, but it turns out to be much, much easier

81
08:31.440 --> 08:39.810
for computers to solve. We can compute GCDs for numbers with many thousands of digits
in the blink of an eye.

82
08:39.810 --> 08:46.860
It's kind of pointless for me to try to show you examples on the screen because we could fill the
entire screen with digits and we'd still be describing

83
08:46.860 --> 08:50.220
easily solved instances of this problem.

84
08:50.220 --> 08:56.730
But if you're interested, follow the link in the video description to the textbook page for this lesson and you'll find code cells

85
08:56.730 --> 09:06.420
for the sorts of computations
that I'm talking about, including ones that compute
GCDs of large numbers, and you can try them out for yourself.

86
09:06.420 --> 09:13.290
The question is why is this possible to compute GCDs so easily?

87
09:13.290 --> 09:18.060
And the answer to that question is that we have efficient
algorithms to compute GCDs.

88
09:18.060 --> 09:28.770
Among them is Euclid's algorithm, which was discovered over 2,000 years ago, but there are also other
efficient GCD algorithms.

89
09:28.770 --> 09:35.730
And of course we're talking about classical algorithms here, so that leads to another question.

90
09:35.730 --> 09:44.280
Could there be an efficient
classical algorithm for integer factorization
that would allow us to factor numbers like RSA1024
in the blink of an eye?

91
09:44.280 --> 09:51.180
And the answer is yes. Absolutely there could be an efficient classical
algorithm for factoring and currently we don't know any way

92
09:51.180 --> 09:57.240
to rule out that possibility. All that we can say is that
we haven't found one yet.

93
09:57.240 --> 10:03.450
For all the classical
factoring algorithms we know, we're still essentially
searching for factors

94
10:03.450 --> 10:08.250
and that puts numbers like
RSA1024 out of our reach.

95
10:08.250 --> 10:12.030
Efficient GCD algorithms,
on the other hand, just don't work that way.

96
10:12.030 --> 10:19.170
They don't search for a
greatest common divisor. They effectively just build
it with a mechanical procedure that's roughly comparable in cost

97
10:19.170 --> 10:25.380
to multiplying the same
two numbers together, and I'll say a little bit more about this later in the lesson.

98
10:25.380 --> 10:31.710
Of course, this is all building
up to Shor's algorithm, which we'll see in the next lesson, which is an efficient quantum algorithm

99
10:31.710 --> 10:37.590
for computing prime factorizations, but we still have some ground
to cover before we get there.

100
10:37.590 --> 10:44.220
Next we're going to talk
about a mathematical framework through which we can measure the computational costs
of different algorithms,

101
10:44.220 --> 10:47.310
including ones we've already talked about.

102
10:47.310 --> 10:55.290
To be clear, we're going to be focusing very narrowly on circuits, which is just a small piece
of a much broader subject.

103
10:55.290 --> 11:02.820
Let's start with a very high level view of an ordinary computation
from the previous lesson, meaning in particular that we're not thinking
about query problems,

104
11:02.820 --> 11:08.760
we're thinking about
problems where the input is given explicitly as a binary string.

105
11:08.760 --> 11:16.050
Like I said in the previous lesson, we could of course allow
other symbols if we chose to, but let's just keep things simple and stick with binary strings

106
11:16.050 --> 11:20.340
for both the input and the output.

107
11:20.340 --> 11:27.720
The computation itself could be modeled or described in a variety of ways such as with the Turing
machine model of computation,

108
11:27.720 --> 11:36.600
Boolean circuits, quantum circuits, or programs written in
a language like Python or any other language of your choice.

109
11:36.600 --> 11:42.420
Like I said a moment ago, we're gonna be focusing on
circuits, Boolean and quantum.

110
11:42.420 --> 11:51.090
First, let's spend a little bit more time talking about the input and the output, which we're assuming are binary strings.

111
11:51.090 --> 11:59.880
Using binary strings, we can encode many different sorts of
mathematical objects, such as numbers, vectors,
matrices, graphs,

112
11:59.880 --> 12:07.050
descriptions of molecules, for instance, as well as lists of all of these objects and other ones as well.

113
12:07.050 --> 12:18.270
As a very simple example, if we wanna encode non-negative
integers as binary strings, we can use binary notation.

114
12:18.270 --> 12:26.730
Here in this table, you'll see the first 13
non-negative integers along with their binary
representations or encodings.

115
12:26.730 --> 12:34.710
Here in the third column, you can see the length of
each of these encodings, which is just the total number of bits you need for the encoding,

116
12:34.710 --> 12:42.210
and here's a simple formula that tells you exactly how many bits
are needed in general for any non-negative integer N.

117
12:42.210 --> 12:47.520
Notice in particular that
the length of the encoding is generally much smaller
than the number itself.

118
12:47.520 --> 12:51.420
It's logarithmic in the number.

119
12:51.420 --> 13:02.280
RSA1024 for instance, has an encoding with length 1,024, but the number itself is of
course much larger than that.

120
13:02.280 --> 13:11.190
This encoding scheme works
for non-negative integers, but if we want to handle
arbitrary integers, including negative ones, we
can simply tack on a sign bit.

121
13:11.190 --> 13:19.140
We can also allow any number of leading zeros in these encodings if we want the encodings
to fill out a block of bits or a register of a fixed size

122
13:19.140 --> 13:22.410
as long as it's big enough. Sometimes that's very convenient.

123
13:22.410 --> 13:26.130
This isn't the only way to encode integers as strings of bits.

124
13:26.130 --> 13:33.570
There are other ways that you could do it, but this is a pretty
standard way to do it.

125
13:33.570 --> 13:43.920
For other sorts of objects that might form the inputs or the outputs to the computational
problems we're interested in, we can come up with
other encoding schemes.

126
13:43.920 --> 13:51.390
For example, think about how
you might encode a vector or a graph as a binary string or think about how you might encode

127
13:51.390 --> 13:58.050
two binary strings into
a single binary string using just the symbol zero and one without a space or any other symbol

128
13:58.050 --> 14:08.190
to separate the two strings. There are certainly ways to
do these things, and in fact, we have a lot of freedom
as to exactly how we do it.

129
14:08.190 --> 14:15.630
Often there won't be a single standard or universally agreed upon way to encode whatever thing we're talking
about as a binary string,

130
14:15.630 --> 14:20.880
but that's okay, we can just pick one or we can invent a new one if we prefer.

131
14:20.880 --> 14:28.620
From a purely formal viewpoint, we're thinking about computations as essentially mechanical transformations on strings of bits

132
14:28.620 --> 14:34.680
and the specifics of whatever
encoding schemes we use are certainly important at some level.

133
14:34.680 --> 14:42.900
But nevertheless, when we're designing and
analyzing algorithms, we usually don't worry all that much about the specifics of
the encoding schemes.

134
14:42.900 --> 14:49.470
If you ask two different people to come up with a way to encode, say, molecules of a certain
type as binary strings,

135
14:49.470 --> 14:55.830
you might expect them to come up with different ways to do it, but if these were reasonable people who knew what they were doing,

136
14:55.830 --> 15:03.000
you could also reasonably expect that it would be a pretty
simple computational process to translate back and forth between the two encoding schemes,

137
15:03.000 --> 15:12.180
most likely requiring a very
straightforward computation that would be quite easy compared to the actual computation
we're interested in.

138
15:12.180 --> 15:20.880
The bottom line is that the details concerning the encoding schemes we use are often quite secondary and our focus is on the
algorithms themselves.

139
15:20.880 --> 15:29.520
None of this is going to be an issue for this lesson, by the way. We're mainly gonna be focusing on problems that concern integers, which we'll assume are encoded in binary,

140
15:29.520 --> 15:33.150
but it's something to be aware of.

141
15:33.150 --> 15:41.250
In general, for whatever sort of problem we're talking about, the input length refers
to the number of bits we need to encode the input,

142
15:41.250 --> 15:48.270
and we view the input length as being the size of the instance of whatever problem we're thinking about.

143
15:48.270 --> 15:55.200
Now, let's consider
the computation itself, which is represented by the
blue rectangle in this figure.

144
15:55.200 --> 16:03.030
The way that we'll measure
the cost of this computation is to count the number of elementary operations that it requires.

145
16:03.030 --> 16:09.630
Intuitively speaking, an elementary operation is one involving a small fixed
number of bits or qubits

146
16:09.630 --> 16:15.600
that can be performed quickly and easily like competing the and of
two bits, for instance.

147
16:15.600 --> 16:23.460
At a formal level,
there are different ways to define what an elementary operation is, depending upon what
computational model we're using.

148
16:23.460 --> 16:30.000
For example, an elementary operation could be one step of a Turing machine if we were using that model.

149
16:30.000 --> 16:39.030
For the purposes of this lesson, we're gonna be focusing on circuit models, as I've already stated, and specifically quantum
and Boolean circuits.

150
16:39.030 --> 16:46.560
When we're working with circuits, it's typical that we think about each gate as representing an elementary operation.

151
16:46.560 --> 16:54.284
We've seen several different quantum gates thus far in the series,
including X, Y and Z gates, Hadamard gates, S and T gates,

152
16:54.284 --> 16:59.550
controlled NOT gates, swap gates, Toffoli gates, and Fredkin gates.

153
16:59.550 --> 17:08.940
We also talked about query gates in the context of the query model, but we're not going to be working within the query model in this lesson, so we won't worry about
query gates for now.

154
17:08.940 --> 17:15.480
We also saw that any unitary operation on any number of qubits
can be viewed as a gate if we want to do that.

155
17:15.480 --> 17:22.830
For the purposes of measuring cost though, that's not going to be very helpful, so what we're going to do is we're simply going
to pick a set of gates

156
17:22.830 --> 17:28.350
and we'll view that set as being our set of elementary operations.

157
17:28.350 --> 17:34.770
First, we'll include the
single qubit unitary gates that you see here,
namely X, Y and Z gates,

158
17:34.770 --> 17:41.340
Hadamard gates and S and T gates, as well as their inverses
or conjugate transposes.

159
17:41.340 --> 17:47.760
We don't actually need all of these gates. As soon as we have Hadamard and T gates, we can implement the rest of them,

160
17:47.760 --> 17:53.100
but just for the sake of convenience, we're gonna include all of them.

161
17:53.100 --> 17:58.719
We'll also include controlled NOT gates, and these will be the only
multiple qubit gates in our set.

162
17:58.719 --> 18:10.260
And finally we'll include single-qubit standard basis measurements so that we can actually get some classical information
coming out of our circuits.

163
18:10.260 --> 18:19.527
If we focus just on the unitary gates and forget about the
measurements for a moment, we obtain what's called
a universal gate set.

164
18:19.527 --> 18:25.950
What that means is that
any unitary operation on any number of qubits can
either be implemented exactly

165
18:25.950 --> 18:31.830
or arbitrarily closely
with a quantum circuit built out of just these gates.

166
18:31.830 --> 18:37.410
In other words, this is a
good enough set of gates that we can build any unitary
operation out of them.

167
18:37.410 --> 18:43.050
Not necessarily exactly, but we can get as good an
approximation as we want.

168
18:43.050 --> 18:50.280
That might require a lot of gates, and it's actually not too hard to reason that it must require a
lot of gates sometimes,

169
18:50.280 --> 18:55.500
but nevertheless, it's always possible.

170
18:55.500 --> 19:02.220
It's not a simple matter to prove that this is a universal gate set though, and we won't discuss how
that's done in the series,

171
19:02.220 --> 19:09.660
but it is a pretty well known fact and there are in fact different
ways that it can be proved.

172
19:09.660 --> 19:18.000
There are also other gate sets that are sometimes used
instead of this one, such as Toffoli gates, Hadamard gates, and S gates in addition to measurements,

173
19:18.000 --> 19:23.160
but this is a pretty standard choice.

174
19:23.160 --> 19:32.520
So in summary, these are
the quantum operations that we'll view as being elementary.

175
19:32.520 --> 19:42.330
For Boolean circuits,
we're going to consider these four gates to be
elementary operations: AND gates, OR gates, NOT gates and FANOUT.

176
19:42.330 --> 19:51.360
FANOUT, by the way, is not
always counted as being a gate, but it's going to be
important for us to do this as we will see later in the lesson.

177
19:51.360 --> 19:56.760
Similar to what we had for
our standard quantum gate set, this set is a little bit redundant.

178
19:56.760 --> 20:02.790
You don't need both AND and OR. You can create either one using the other with three NOT gates,

179
20:02.790 --> 20:08.040
but it doesn't hurt to include both and it's just convenient.

180
20:08.040 --> 20:15.480
As you may already know, this is a universal gate set
for deterministic computations, meaning that any function
from bits to bits

181
20:15.480 --> 20:21.570
can be implemented with a Boolean circuit composed of gates from this collection.

182
20:21.570 --> 20:28.980
Once again, just like we
had for quantum circuits, this doesn't mean that every function can be implemented efficiently
by a Boolean circuit,

183
20:28.980 --> 20:36.780
and indeed most functions
can only be implemented with very large circuits
for the simple reason that there are lots and lots of functions

184
20:36.780 --> 20:43.080
and they can't all have small circuits. There just aren't enough
small circuits to go around.

185
20:43.080 --> 20:48.270
Universality is easier
to prove in this case than in the quantum case as it turns out.

186
20:48.270 --> 20:56.250
So if you don't already
know how to prove it, give it some thought and
see if you can figure it out if you're so inclined.

187
20:56.250 --> 21:03.420
Now that we've decided on the
gates we're going to allow and we're going to consider
to be elementary operations, we can think about how many of them

188
21:03.420 --> 21:08.520
are required to perform
various computations.

189
21:08.520 --> 21:13.620
To do that, we'll make
use of this definition for the size of a circuit.

190
21:13.620 --> 21:18.750
This definition works for both
Boolean and quantum circuits and it's very simple.

191
21:18.750 --> 21:23.640
The size of a circuit is the
total number of gates it has.

192
21:23.640 --> 21:31.740
For example, if we return
to the same example we've seen several times, which is our Boolean circuit for computing the exclusive OR of two bits,

193
21:31.740 --> 21:38.460
we see that it has size seven
because there's seven gates, two FANOUT gates, two NOT gates,

194
21:38.460 --> 21:46.050
two AND gates and one OR gate. If we decided not to count
FANOUT gates, which is common, it would have size equal to five,

195
21:46.050 --> 21:51.510
but we are going to count FANOUT gates, so its size is seven.

196
21:51.510 --> 21:57.120
The size of a circuit
corresponds to the number of elementary operations
we need to perform.

197
21:57.120 --> 22:03.900
So if we were to perform
those operations sequentially and the size would tell
us how long it would take,

198
22:03.900 --> 22:09.900
so you can think about a circuit size as representing sequential running time.

199
22:09.900 --> 22:15.600
This is going to be how we
measure computational cost for the purposes of this lesson.

200
22:15.600 --> 22:24.870
There is another property
of circuits though that can also be viewed as the amount of time
required to run a circuit, and that's the circuit's depth.

201
22:24.870 --> 22:32.460
To be precise, the depth
is the maximum number of gates encountered on any path from an input wire to an output wire,

202
22:32.460 --> 22:39.150
which is equivalent to the number of layers of gates we need
to create the circuit, where a layer refers to a bunch of gates

203
22:39.150 --> 22:45.660
that could be performed simultaneously because they don't have
any wires in common.

204
22:45.660 --> 22:52.950
For example, our circuit
from before has depth four, and we can see directly from the diagram that there are four layers.

205
22:52.950 --> 23:04.260
The FANOUT gates can be
performed simultaneously, the NOT gates can be
performed simultaneously and the AND gates can be
performed simultaneously as well.

206
23:04.260 --> 23:10.710
So we can think about circuit depth as representing parallel running time.

207
23:10.710 --> 23:17.790
Circuit depth is certainly an interesting and important notion and there are some very
sophisticated techniques that can be used to reduce

208
23:17.790 --> 23:24.870
the depth required for some computations, sometimes quite dramatically, in fact, but it's an advanced topic

209
23:24.870 --> 23:29.280
and we're not gonna have too much more to say about it in this series.

210
23:29.280 --> 23:35.550
So once again, we'll
measure computational cost in terms of circuit
size or in other words,

211
23:35.550 --> 23:40.950
the number of elementary operations required to perform a computation.

212
23:40.950 --> 23:48.810
At the beginning of the lesson, we talked about the integer
factorization problem and we saw that the time required for an algorithm to solve this problem

213
23:48.810 --> 23:55.320
can increase as inputs grow in length, and this is typically
the issue we focus on

214
23:55.320 --> 23:58.320
when we're analyzing algorithms.

215
23:58.320 --> 24:05.730
That is, we're interested in how the costs of running algorithms scale as inputs get larger and larger.

216
24:05.730 --> 24:09.780
Of course, this sort of scaling isn't the only thing that matters.

217
24:09.780 --> 24:16.470
For example, we may simply be interested in finding the factors
of RSA1024 and that's it.

218
24:16.470 --> 24:22.350
So in a case like that, we'd be talking about a
single problem instance where nothing is growing.

219
24:22.350 --> 24:31.050
But when we're thinking about algorithms, the way that their costs
scale matters a great deal and it tells us a lot
about the algorithms.

220
24:31.050 --> 24:37.320
This point of view is
consistent with the idea that algorithms are fundamental, and as I talked about before,

221
24:37.320 --> 24:45.180
as time goes on and technology advances, they will be deployed against
larger and larger inputs.

222
24:45.180 --> 24:50.760
But notice that while inputs to computational problems
can grow in size, circuits don't grow.

223
24:50.760 --> 24:54.360
Each circuit has a fixed size.

224
24:54.360 --> 25:01.830
And for that reason, if we want to describe an
algorithm using circuits, we're actually going to need a family of circuits to do that,

225
25:01.830 --> 25:08.610
and by a family of circuits, we mean a collection of circuits that gets larger and larger so that we can accommodate inputs

226
25:08.610 --> 25:15.090
as they get larger and larger. For example, let's consider a classical deterministic algorithm

227
25:15.090 --> 25:21.150
for the integer factorization problem, maybe one based on trial division, but the specifics don't really matter

228
25:21.150 --> 25:24.390
for the sake of this example.

229
25:24.390 --> 25:31.020
We could in principle
describe such an algorithm using a family of Boolean circuits where if we want to factor a number

230
25:31.020 --> 25:38.610
whose binary representation has N-bits, we grab the circuit CN from our family and we input the number
that we want to factor

231
25:38.610 --> 25:42.300
into the input bits of that circuit.

232
25:42.300 --> 25:49.800
Sometimes we might choose to parameterize these
circuits in different ways, so it might not always be the case that the Nth circuit has N input bits,

233
25:49.800 --> 25:58.620
but that's a pretty typical way to do it. Naturally, as the input
lengths get longer, we would expect the circuits
in this family to get larger

234
25:58.620 --> 26:05.910
reflecting the fact that
factoring four bit numbers is a lot easier than factoring 1,024 bit numbers, for instance.

235
26:05.910 --> 26:13.830
And so, with that in mind, we measure the cost of such
an algorithm by a function, which tells us how many
elementary operations

236
26:13.830 --> 26:21.300
we need for each possible input length, and we can do this for both classical and quantum algorithms.

237
26:21.300 --> 26:27.360
As an example, let's consider the problem of integer addition, which is certainly much
simpler than factoring

238
26:27.360 --> 26:30.660
or even competing GCDs.

239
26:30.660 --> 26:36.810
Just to keep things simple, let's suppose that both N and
M are non-negative integers and that they're represented

240
26:36.810 --> 26:40.680
by binary strings having the same length.

241
26:40.680 --> 26:45.550
How might we build Boolean circuits that add these two numbers together?

242
26:45.550 --> 26:52.110
Well, let's start with an algorithm, the standard algorithm for addition, which is the base two analog of the method

243
26:52.110 --> 27:01.200
that I presume we all learned for adding numbers together with a
pencil and a piece of paper, so we start with the
least significant bits,

244
27:01.200 --> 27:07.530
add them together, and that gives us the least
significant bit of the result along with a carry bit
that we have to consider

245
27:07.530 --> 27:14.910
when we move to the next position. And we continue moving through the bits, generating output bits
along with carry bits

246
27:14.910 --> 27:18.150
until we get to the end.

247
27:18.150 --> 27:23.040
This method can be
expressed pretty directly in terms of Boolean circuits.

248
27:23.040 --> 27:29.340
One way to think about it is to start off with a small circuit for adding two single bit integers together.

249
27:29.340 --> 27:35.700
That'll give us a number
between zero and two, where the lesser significant bit is the XOR of the input bits

250
27:35.700 --> 27:41.940
and the more significant bit, or the carry bit if you prefer, is the AND of the two input bits.

251
27:41.940 --> 27:48.120
Sometimes we refer to a circuit that performs these
two operations together as a half adder.

252
27:48.120 --> 27:54.143
That works fine when there
are just two input bits, but if we want to add together integers with more than just one bit each,

253
27:54.143 --> 27:58.500
we're going to need to deal
with the carry bits somehow.

254
27:58.500 --> 28:07.170
So what we can do is to cascade
two half adders together and take the OR of the
carry bits they produce to create what's called a full adder,

255
28:07.170 --> 28:12.150
which is basically a Boolean circuit for adding three single
bit numbers together.

256
28:12.150 --> 28:18.510
And once we have a full adder, we can add numbers together
simply by cascading, proceeding from the least significant bit

257
28:18.510 --> 28:29.010
to the most significant bit. We're basically just implementing the standard addition algorithm using the full adders to
deal with the carry bits.

258
28:29.010 --> 28:32.070
So what's the cost of this computation?

259
28:32.070 --> 28:38.310
Well, we need seven elementary
gates for each XOR gate, which means 10 gates for a half adder

260
28:38.310 --> 28:45.120
and therefore 21 gates for a full adder, which is two half adders plus an OR gate.

261
28:45.120 --> 28:52.290
So at the end of the day, if our input numbers both have AND bits, we need a half adder for
the least significant bit

262
28:52.290 --> 29:03.030
and a full adder for every other bit, and the end result is 21 times N minus one plus 10 or 21 N minus 11 gates in total.

263
29:03.030 --> 29:12.750
If we decided for some reason that we didn't want to
count the FANOUT gates and we included the XOR
gates in our gate set, we'd need five N minus
three gates in total.

264
29:12.750 --> 29:19.260
It's nice to know exactly how many gates or elementary operations are required to perform different computations,

265
29:19.260 --> 29:22.290
such as we just saw with integer addition.

266
29:22.290 --> 29:29.010
And of course, if we actually want to implement these computations, we need to know these details.

267
29:29.010 --> 29:36.150
But if we always go into this much detail, especially for more
complicated algorithms, we'll be very quickly buried in details

268
29:36.150 --> 29:41.220
that in many cases have
secondary importance.

269
29:41.220 --> 29:48.120
One way to simplify matters that's very common in the
analysis of algorithms is to make use of big-O notation,

270
29:48.120 --> 29:54.030
which allows us to express
and compare rates of growth in a pretty simple way
that's very convenient.

271
29:54.030 --> 29:58.830
And here you can see the definition that underlies this notation.

272
29:58.830 --> 30:05.940
Suppose that we have
two functions G and H, which we can think of as taking non-negative integer
values for simplicity,

273
30:05.940 --> 30:14.010
although that's not actually required. Maybe G and H represent costs of different computations, for instance.

274
30:14.010 --> 30:20.340
We then say that G is big-O of H, which is traditionally written
with an equal sign like this.

275
30:20.340 --> 30:27.870
If G of N is at most some
positive constant C times H of N, so long as N is large enough.

276
30:27.870 --> 30:31.710
So this is about what
happens when N gets large.

277
30:31.710 --> 30:38.340
Formally, what large enough means is that there's some choice of N zero so that the inequality is true

278
30:38.340 --> 30:41.430
whenever N is at least N zero.

279
30:41.430 --> 30:45.660
The key here is that these
numbers C and N zero are fixed.

280
30:45.660 --> 30:51.870
They can be any numbers at
all, but whatever they are, they can't change as N grows.

281
30:51.870 --> 30:58.440
If you've never seen this
kind of definition before, it might take some getting used to and you can find resources
that will explain this concept

282
30:58.440 --> 31:03.630
in a lot more detail than
I'm able to in this lesson.

283
31:03.630 --> 31:13.500
Usually what we do is to choose
the function H to be simple in order to express something about how quickly the function G grows.

284
31:13.500 --> 31:19.560
For example, the function whose value is 17 times N cubed minus 257

285
31:19.560 --> 31:27.540
times N squared plus
65,537 is big-O of N cubed, and you can fit this
example to the definition

286
31:27.540 --> 31:30.630
by picking C and N zero appropriately.

287
31:30.630 --> 31:40.080
For example, if we take C to be 18, then we'll have that
the expression is indeed at most 18 times N cubed
as long as N is big enough.

288
31:40.080 --> 31:47.370
Tying this notation back to the
example of integer addition, what we can now say is that there exists a family of Boolean circuits

289
31:47.370 --> 31:54.570
for adding non-negative integers together such that the size of the N circuit, meaning the one that works
for inputs of length N

290
31:54.570 --> 32:05.580
is big-O of N. The actual size of CN
according to our analysis was 21 times N minus 11,
but that's big-O of N.

291
32:05.580 --> 32:12.030
Now it's not always a smart thing to do to throw away details like this, but here it makes sense

292
32:12.030 --> 32:19.530
because it reveals the essential nature of the standard addition algorithm, which is that its cost scales linearly

293
32:19.530 --> 32:28.170
in the size of the numbers
that we're adding together, and this expression is not sensitive to some of the low level
details of our model,

294
32:28.170 --> 32:32.910
such as precisely which gates we consider to be elementary operations.

295
32:32.910 --> 32:42.030
For instance, if we decided that XOR gates should be considered as
elementary operations or that FANOUT gates shouldn't
count as gates or both,

296
32:42.030 --> 32:47.550
we'd still have that integer addition can be computed at cost big-O of N.

297
32:47.550 --> 32:52.620
Here's another example of
a computational problem, multiplication of integers.

298
32:52.620 --> 32:58.050
Similar to addition, we can ask what the cost
of this computation is.

299
32:58.050 --> 33:06.420
If we consider the standard
multiplication algorithm, meaning the base two analog of the method for multiplying numbers
taught in elementary schools,

300
33:06.420 --> 33:14.520
which is basically just
shifting and adding when we're working with numbers in binary, we find that there are Boolean circuits having size big-O of N squared

301
33:14.520 --> 33:17.790
for multiplying N-bit integers.

302
33:17.790 --> 33:24.870
I won't go through this one in detail. Of course the circuits are a
little bit more complicated than the ones for addition, but if you think about the way

303
33:24.870 --> 33:30.330
that the standard
multiplication algorithm works, it shouldn't come as a surprise.

304
33:30.330 --> 33:39.900
In essence, we need to
do roughly N additions, each of which has linear cost, and so we end up with
quadratic cost overall.

305
33:39.900 --> 33:49.020
This can be generalized. If one of the numbers has N bits and the other one has N bits, then we need circuits of
size big-O of N times M.

306
33:49.020 --> 33:56.370
Here, by the way, we are actually using an extension of the big-O notation where we have multiple variables, but it can be extended like this,

307
33:56.370 --> 34:06.088
and if you're interested
in the specific details, I'll refer you to the textbook
content for the lesson, which again is linked in
the video description.

308
34:06.088 --> 34:14.880
It's actually possible
to multiply together two N-bit integers in a way
that's asymptotically superior to the standard multiplication algorithm.

309
34:14.880 --> 34:23.670
In particular, the Schonhage-Strassen multiplication algorithm
multiplies two N-bit integers with a cost of big-O of
N times the length of N

310
34:23.670 --> 34:29.940
times the length of the length of N. So as N gets large, like
tens of thousands of bits,

311
34:29.940 --> 34:40.350
this is actually a more
efficient way to multiply, but it's complicated and the overhead does make it impractical
for smaller numbers.

312
34:40.350 --> 34:43.350
So let's add multiplication
to our list of examples.

313
34:43.350 --> 34:51.450
And just for simplicity, let's list the cost given by the standard multiplication algorithm, which is big-O of N squared.

314
34:51.450 --> 34:58.050
So once again, we're focusing on the essential nature of this cost, which is that it scales quadratically

315
34:58.050 --> 35:05.640
or sub quadratically if we use asymptotically superior methods.

316
35:05.640 --> 35:11.820
We can also consider the
problem of integer division, which is stated precisely on the screen.

317
35:11.820 --> 35:20.550
Here we're talking about computing a quotient and a remainder, so the answer consists
of two integers, Q and R.

318
35:20.550 --> 35:28.620
Once again, there's a standard
algorithm for division and it also has quadratic
cost and like multiplication,

319
35:28.620 --> 35:36.060
there are in fact asymptotically
superior algorithms.

320
35:36.060 --> 35:41.700
So how do GCD algorithms compare?

321
35:41.700 --> 35:49.410
Well, Euclid's algorithm turns
out to have quadratic cost, and that's what I meant
earlier in the lesson when I said that we can compute GCDs

322
35:49.410 --> 35:54.210
at roughly the same cost as multiplying two numbers together.

323
35:54.210 --> 36:00.600
Once again, there are
asymptotically superior algorithms along similar lines to
addition and multiplication,

324
36:00.600 --> 36:05.700
although the cost is a little
bit higher in this case, as least as far as we know.

325
36:05.700 --> 36:12.270
I'll mention just one more example of a problem to add to this list, and that's modular exponentiation.

326
36:12.270 --> 36:20.400
Here there are three input
numbers, K, M, and N, and the goal is to compute
N to the power K modulo-M,

327
36:20.400 --> 36:25.170
which means the remainder
after we divide by M.

328
36:25.170 --> 36:34.830
It's not at all obvious, but we can compute modular
exponentiation at qubit cost, meaning big-O of N cubed
for N-bit integers.

329
36:34.830 --> 36:39.840
The way to do this one is not to first compute N to the power K and then compute the remainder.

330
36:39.840 --> 36:46.950
Even writing down into the power K could require exponentially many bits, so that approach won't work.

331
36:46.950 --> 36:54.660
Instead, we can use an algorithm
called the power algorithm, which is also called repeated squaring where everything is done modulo-M

332
36:54.660 --> 37:01.170
and we use the bits of
K to iteratively square and multiply in a way
that makes it all work.

333
37:01.170 --> 37:10.680
So this one is more
expensive than the others, but we can still perform
modular exponentiation quite quickly on numbers
with many thousands of bits.

334
37:10.680 --> 37:16.770
So how do the costs of these tasks compare with integer factorization?

335
37:16.770 --> 37:22.980
If we start simple and
think about trial division where we first check to see if two is a factor of the input number

336
37:22.980 --> 37:33.630
and then check three and so on, we'll end up with a pretty
expensive algorithm, big-O of N squared times
two to the power N over two.

337
37:33.630 --> 37:41.640
Each division takes quadratic time and in the worst case, we'll need to search for prime factors up to the square root of the input number,

338
37:41.640 --> 37:48.120
and that's where the N
over two is coming from. If we haven't found a
prime factor at that point, we can just stop because then

339
37:48.120 --> 37:51.480
the input number itself must be prime.

340
37:51.480 --> 38:01.560
This is extremely expensive because N appears as an exponent in this expression, which is to say that this
algorithm has exponential cost.

341
38:01.560 --> 38:09.060
In contrast, all of the examples that we have in this box here have what we call polynomial cost where N gets raised to a power,

342
38:09.060 --> 38:13.920
but that power is always a fixed number that doesn't grow as
the input length grows.

343
38:13.920 --> 38:17.760
In these cases, the powers
are one, two, and three.

344
38:17.760 --> 38:25.908
I'll come back to polynomial versus exponential cost in just a moment, but first, let's finish off
what we know about factoring.

345
38:25.908 --> 38:34.170
Earlier I mentioned
the number field sieve, which is the best
factoring algorithm we have in terms of the way its cost scales.

346
38:34.170 --> 38:40.470
In fact, the cost of this algorithm isn't actually rigorously proven because it's connected with some open questions about number theory,

347
38:40.470 --> 38:44.970
but it is conjectured to have
a cost that looks like this.

348
38:44.970 --> 38:50.730
This time the big-O is in the exponent, but I'm gonna sweep that
detail under the rug.

349
38:50.730 --> 38:57.450
The key takeaway is that it's significantly better
than trial division because although N does
appear in the exponent,

350
38:57.450 --> 39:04.170
it's raised to the power 1/3 and that translates to a much lower cost and that's why this algorithm

351
39:04.170 --> 39:10.890
can handle numbers like RSA250, whereas trial division
most certainly can't.

352
39:10.890 --> 39:17.670
It's still exponential though in the sense that a power of N is appearing in an exponent, and so, as a result,

353
39:17.670 --> 39:22.440
it still can't handle
numbers like RSA1024.

354
39:22.440 --> 39:28.320
Now let me say a little bit more about polynomial cost
versus exponential cost.

355
39:28.320 --> 39:34.920
We say that an algorithm
has polynomial cost if its cost is big-O of N to the power B,

356
39:34.920 --> 39:42.030
where B can be any positive number, but the key is that B has to be fixed, meaning that it doesn't change

357
39:42.030 --> 39:45.990
as the input length end grows.

358
39:45.990 --> 39:54.780
For the examples we saw a moment ago, meaning integer addition, multiplication, division, computing GCDs
and modular exponentiation,

359
39:54.780 --> 39:57.990
we had that B was either
one, two or three.

360
39:57.990 --> 40:01.710
So these are all
polynomial cost algorithms.

361
40:01.710 --> 40:06.570
But when we say polynomial
cost more generally, B could be any positive number.

362
40:06.570 --> 40:11.520
It could even be one million,
but it has to be fixed.

363
40:11.520 --> 40:19.770
As a very rough abstraction, algorithms having polynomial
cost are typically viewed as representing efficient algorithms.

364
40:19.770 --> 40:26.730
It's definitely an oversimplification, but as a rough guideline, you can think about a
polynomial cost algorithm

365
40:26.730 --> 40:34.380
as somehow making use
of a problem's structure to construct a solution as opposed to a brute
force type of approach

366
40:34.380 --> 40:39.450
or an exhaustive search
over a very large space.

367
40:39.450 --> 40:45.660
Of course, an algorithm whose cost scales as N to the one million
on inputs of length N

368
40:45.660 --> 40:52.710
would not reasonably
be viewed as efficient, and we wouldn't expect to be
able to run it on large inputs.

369
40:52.710 --> 41:00.000
But still even an N to
the one million algorithm must be doing something clever that somehow reflects the structure

370
41:00.000 --> 41:06.330
of whatever problem it solves to avoid the exponential scaling in cost that would be associated with

371
41:06.330 --> 41:10.200
an exhaustive search over a large domain.

372
41:10.200 --> 41:18.360
And in practice, the identification of a polynomial cost algorithm is really just a first
step towards efficiency.

373
41:18.360 --> 41:26.850
If a problem is important
and someone discovers the very first polynomial
cost algorithm for it, maybe having a very large exponent,

374
41:26.850 --> 41:35.100
you can be reasonably sure that algorithm designers
will find improvements that cause that exponent to come down.

375
41:35.100 --> 41:43.950
In essence, you can
think about the existence of a polynomial cost
algorithm for a problem as demonstrating the feasibility
of solving that problem

376
41:43.950 --> 41:53.010
on reasonably large inputs, but there still could be a lot of work required to reach true efficiency.

377
41:53.010 --> 42:01.350
In complexity theory, it's typical to say that an algorithm's cost
scales sub-exponentially if the cost is big-O of two to the power N

378
42:01.350 --> 42:07.620
to the power epsilon for every positive real number epsilon, and if it's not sub-exponential,

379
42:07.620 --> 42:14.970
then it's exponential, or it could even be super-exponential like two to the two to the N,
which is doubly exponential,

380
42:14.970 --> 42:22.350
but as long as the output
isn't super-exponentially long, every problem can actually be
computed by a Boolean circuit

381
42:22.350 --> 42:32.340
having exponential cost as it turns out. So the important distinction here is between polynomial
and exponential cost.

382
42:32.340 --> 42:38.970
We don't know of any sub-exponential cost classical algorithms for
integer factorization.

383
42:38.970 --> 42:46.890
For example, the number field sieve's cost is not big-O of two to
the N to the epsilon when epsilon is 1/3 or less,

384
42:46.890 --> 42:50.610
so it doesn't satisfy this definition.

385
42:50.610 --> 42:56.700
It's undoubtedly a very clever algorithm, but it's still a sieve and we're still effectively searching

386
42:56.700 --> 43:02.640
over a very large space to identify factors of a given number.

387
43:02.640 --> 43:08.640
As we'll see in the next lesson, there is in fact a polynomial
cost quantum algorithm for integer factorization.

388
43:08.640 --> 43:17.130
Shor's algorithm has polynomial cost and specifically it has qubit cost, similar to modular exponentiation.

389
43:17.130 --> 43:22.170
Another class of problems that
you might be familiar with is the class of NP-complete problems.

390
43:22.170 --> 43:27.960
I won't go into what NP-complete problems are in this lesson, but you can look them
up if you're interested.

391
43:27.960 --> 43:32.490
It's conjectured that
none of these problems have sub-exponential cost.

392
43:32.490 --> 43:41.970
That's essentially a circuit-based version of what's sometimes called the
exponential time hypothesis, but so far nobody's been able
to figure out how to prove it.

393
43:41.970 --> 43:48.210
In fact, we can't even prove that there aren't linear cost algorithms for NP-complete problems.

394
43:48.210 --> 44:00.750
It's just really tough, at
least as far as we know, to rule out the possibility
of a future discovery of an incredibly creative
algorithm for these problems.

395
44:00.750 --> 44:06.600
Here's a figure that
illustrates the relationship between polynomial and exponential cost.

396
44:06.600 --> 44:14.880
On the X axis, we have the input length to whatever problem we're thinking about, and the Y axis represents the
cost of solving that problem

397
44:14.880 --> 44:20.850
or you can think about
it as the time required to solve the problem if you prefer.

398
44:20.850 --> 44:24.660
An exponential cost algorithm
might scale like this.

399
44:24.660 --> 44:31.170
For short inputs, the cost might not be particularly high, like factoring the
number 12, for instance,

400
44:31.170 --> 44:38.220
but as the input length gets longer, the cost is eventually going to blow up.

401
44:38.220 --> 44:43.980
A polynomial cost algorithm,
on the other hand, might have a scaling that looks like this.

402
44:43.980 --> 44:51.750
The cost will still increase in general as inputs get longer, and it might even cost more than the exponential cost
algorithm for some inputs,

403
44:51.750 --> 44:59.370
but eventually it's gonna
be a lot less expensive than the exponential cost algorithm and it doesn't blow up
in the same extreme way

404
44:59.370 --> 45:03.780
that exponential cost algorithms do.

405
45:03.780 --> 45:11.100
So if we imagine that we
have some maximum cost that we're willing to spend, or a maximum amount of time that we're willing to wait for an answer,

406
45:11.100 --> 45:19.320
if you prefer to think about time, then the exponential cost algorithm will only work for inputs
up to a given length,

407
45:19.320 --> 45:25.890
whereas, in general, the
polynomial cost algorithm will allow us to solve the
problem for larger inputs.

408
45:25.890 --> 45:32.700
And that's why, for instance, we can easily compute GCDs for numbers with many thousands of
bits, but in the worst case,

409
45:32.700 --> 45:36.240
we can't factor numbers of this size.

410
45:36.240 --> 45:43.470
In the last part of the lesson, we'll turn our attention to implementing classical computations
on quantum computers.

411
45:43.470 --> 45:51.480
More specifically, we'll
see that any computation that can be performed by a Boolean circuit can also be performed by a quantum circuit

412
45:51.480 --> 45:59.550
at roughly the same cost. Moreover, this can be
done in a clean manner that's important if we
wanna run these computations

413
45:59.550 --> 46:08.280
as sub routines inside of
larger quantum computations, and I'll explain what I mean by clean when we get further into the discussion.

414
46:08.280 --> 46:12.360
We're going to make use of
Toffoli gates in this process.

415
46:12.360 --> 46:18.810
Recall that Toffoli gates are controlled-controlled-NOT gates, so their action on standard basis states

416
46:18.810 --> 46:22.890
is as you see here on the screen.

417
46:22.890 --> 46:28.620
Notice that we can also
think about Toffoli gates as being like query gates
for the AND function.

418
46:28.620 --> 46:36.630
That's not to say that they are query gates in a literal sense. As I mentioned at the start of the lesson, we're not working within the
query model at this point,

419
46:36.630 --> 46:42.240
but rather, their action follows the same pattern as a query gate.

420
46:42.240 --> 46:49.110
We can think of the binary values A and B as the inputs to the AND function and like a query gate,

421
46:49.110 --> 46:55.920
these values get echoed
as part of the output and the value of the function, meaning the logical AND of A and B

422
46:55.920 --> 47:03.000
gets XORed onto the bottom qubit. Now, we haven't included Toffoli gates in our standard gate set.

423
47:03.000 --> 47:11.190
We could change our mind if we wanted to, but we don't really need to
do that because alternatively, we can implement Toffoli
gates using Hadamard gates,

424
47:11.190 --> 47:16.560
T and T dagger gates
and controlled NOT gates like you see right here.

425
47:16.560 --> 47:24.090
It's not at all obvious
that this particular circuit implements a Toffoli gate, but it does, and you can either take my word for it

426
47:24.090 --> 47:30.150
or multiply everything out for yourself to get some extra practice, or you can just ask Qiskit or Python

427
47:30.150 --> 47:34.650
or any software that multiplies matrices to do the multiplication for you.

428
47:34.650 --> 47:40.440
And you can check out the
textbook content for the lesson to see this done using Qiskit.

429
47:40.440 --> 47:47.190
Now we can move on to simulating Boolean gates with quantum circuits and all we'll need to
do this are NOT gates,

430
47:47.190 --> 47:50.850
controlled NOT gates and Toffoli gates.

431
47:50.850 --> 47:59.970
These operations are all deterministic in addition to being unitary and sometimes we describe
operations like this as being reversible, and in fact,

432
47:59.970 --> 48:08.970
the study of reversible computation predates quantum computing and that's where this entire
procedure actually comes from.

433
48:08.970 --> 48:15.251
The Boolean gates we need to
worry about are NOT gates, Hadamard gates and FANOUT gates,

434
48:15.251 --> 48:21.510
And what we're going to show is that we can implement these gates, or simulate them if you
prefer, using NOT gates,

435
48:21.510 --> 48:25.200
controlled NOT gates and Toffoli gates.

436
48:25.200 --> 48:32.430
To be clear, what we
want are quantum circuits that allow us to compute the values of the Boolean gates that I just mentioned

437
48:32.430 --> 48:38.070
when we give them qubits in
standard basis states as input.

438
48:38.070 --> 48:43.980
For arbitrary quantum state inputs, the action will be determined
by linearity as usual.

439
48:43.980 --> 48:52.500
We don't need to do anything
special with the NOT gates. NOT gates are NOT gates and they can be implemented directly.

440
48:52.500 --> 48:58.410
And OR gates can be simulated
using Toffoli and NOT gates.

441
48:58.410 --> 49:05.220
AND gates are easy, particularly in light of what I just said a few moments ago about Toffoli gates being essentially

442
49:05.220 --> 49:09.570
query gate implementations
of the AND function.

443
49:09.570 --> 49:15.810
To be precise, what we can do is to introduce a new qubit initialized to the zero state

444
49:15.810 --> 49:23.040
and let that qubit be the
target of our Toffoli gate and let the two input
qubits be the controls.

445
49:23.040 --> 49:33.750
Different names are given
to extra qubits like this, which are often introduced
into quantum computations and I'll call them workspace
qubits just to pick a name.

446
49:33.750 --> 49:40.650
Our typical assumption on workspace qubits is that they start out in the zero state and we can often return
them to the zero state

447
49:40.650 --> 49:44.280
when we're done with them, but not always.

448
49:44.280 --> 49:50.940
In the diagram we have a cat zero inside of the dotted rectangle to indicate that the
initialization of this qubit

449
49:50.940 --> 49:58.710
is part of the process, and if you don't have a
fresh qubit like this, you're not gonna be able
to do this simulation.

450
49:58.710 --> 50:06.180
The bottom output qubit
is the one we care about because that's the result
of the AND operation and we're basically
done with the other two

451
50:06.180 --> 50:09.300
so they can stay inside of the box.

452
50:09.300 --> 50:15.600
In fact, you could even imagine that getting rid of these two qubits is part of the job of
simulating this AND gate,

453
50:15.600 --> 50:19.800
kind of like garbage that
needs to be cleaned up.

454
50:19.800 --> 50:24.930
But anyway, that's how we
can simulate an AND gate.

455
50:24.930 --> 50:29.790
Now that we know how to do AND gates, we can do OR gates using
one of the De Morgan laws.

456
50:29.790 --> 50:38.580
If you put NOT gates on the two inputs in the output of an AND
gate, you'll get an OR gate, so it's as simple as that.

457
50:38.580 --> 50:45.840
And the last one is FANOUT, and for this one, all we
need is a controlled NOT gate along with a workspace qubit.

458
50:45.840 --> 50:53.100
Specifically, if we
set the workspace qubit to be the target, we effectively just copy whatever standard basis state comes in,

459
50:53.100 --> 50:56.550
so that acts like a FANOUT gate.

460
50:56.550 --> 50:59.550
So we have all our gates.

461
50:59.550 --> 51:04.980
And now that we have all of our gates, we can move on to circuits.

462
51:04.980 --> 51:11.070
Let's suppose that we have
some Boolean circuit named C, and this can be whatever
Boolean circuit you choose

463
51:11.070 --> 51:16.020
as long as it's composed of
AND or NOT and FANOUT gates.

464
51:16.020 --> 51:24.480
We'll let T be the number of gates in C and we'll give the name F to whatever function it is that C computes.

465
51:24.480 --> 51:30.960
So we can think of F as having the form that you see right here, where N is the number of input bits of C,

466
51:30.960 --> 51:35.730
M is the number of output bits and sigma is the binary alphabet.

467
51:35.730 --> 51:40.320
And what we do is to simply go one by one through the gates of C.

468
51:40.320 --> 51:46.380
We leave the NOT gates alone and we replace the others with the simulations
that I just described.

469
51:46.380 --> 51:53.760
So if C looks like this, then what we get is a circuit
R that looks like this.

470
51:53.760 --> 52:01.050
In this diagram, all
of the workspace qubits we need for the simulations have been pulled out of their boxes and collected on the bottom.

471
52:01.050 --> 52:09.240
So K is the total number of
workspace qubits we need, which is one for each of the gates of C except for the NOT gates.

472
52:09.240 --> 52:15.900
For the output of R, we have the qubits that
correspond to the output of C, and here those qubits
are depicted on the top,

473
52:15.900 --> 52:20.070
although it's not actually going to matter at the end of all of this
whether they're on top or not.

474
52:20.070 --> 52:27.030
To be precise, assuming that we've run R on a standard basis state corresponding to an
arbitrary N-bit string X,

475
52:27.030 --> 52:32.700
these M output qubits will be in the standard basis state
corresponding to F of X.

476
52:32.700 --> 52:36.660
We also have all of the leftover qubits from the AND and the OR gates.

477
52:36.660 --> 52:43.260
We still need to account for them, and if we gather them all together, they'll be in some standard basis state.

478
52:43.260 --> 52:49.680
Whatever the standard basis state is has to be some function of the string X, and we're gonna give
that function the name G.

479
52:49.680 --> 52:57.030
So G is a new function that's
determined by the gates of C that tells us what state
these leftover qubits are in

480
52:57.030 --> 53:04.080
after R is run. G is the next letter after F, so that's one reason to
call this function G,

481
53:04.080 --> 53:08.070
but another reason to call it G is because G is short for garbage.

482
53:08.070 --> 53:16.380
These are all garbage qubits, and in particular, we
have two garbage qubits for each AND gate and for each OR gate.

483
53:16.380 --> 53:20.040
The total number of gates
we need is big-O of T.

484
53:20.040 --> 53:25.320
That's because for each gate of C, we need a bounded number of quantum gates.

485
53:25.320 --> 53:31.740
The OR gate is the most expensive one. For that one, we need three NOT gates along with one Toffoli gate,

486
53:31.740 --> 53:35.520
and a Toffoli gate costs us 15 gates from our standard gate set.

487
53:35.520 --> 53:40.170
So that's at most 18 gates
in R for each gate of C.

488
53:40.170 --> 53:48.840
If you wanted to optimize this, you could, but for the purposes of a
rough asymptotic analysis, we can simply say that
R has big-O of T gates.

489
53:48.840 --> 53:55.200
So we've managed to
compute the same function F that the original Boolean
circuit C computed,

490
53:55.200 --> 53:59.730
and we've done this at a cost that's linear in the size of C.

491
53:59.730 --> 54:04.050
If all we care about is
computing this function F, then we're done.

492
54:04.050 --> 54:10.140
But unfortunately, we do
have these garbage qubits and these garbage qubits
are generally going to ruin

493
54:10.140 --> 54:16.530
the interference patterns that make quantum algorithms work if we try to use this
circuit R as a subroutine

494
54:16.530 --> 54:20.280
inside of a larger quantum algorithm.

495
54:20.280 --> 54:27.540
But we can in fact get
rid of this garbage, and the way that we can do
this is to make use of the fact that the circuit R can be inverted,

496
54:27.540 --> 54:31.986
or in other words, we
can run it in reverse.

497
54:31.986 --> 54:38.520
To illustrate how this works, let's imagine that we first run R and then we run R in reverse,

498
54:38.520 --> 54:42.180
which we can express as R dagger.

499
54:42.180 --> 54:52.110
To be clear about this, what it means is that we apply the gates
of R in the reverse order and we take the inverses
of each of the gates.

500
54:52.110 --> 54:58.890
NOT gates, controlled NOT
gates and Toffoli gates are actually their own inverses, so if we're thinking in
terms of these gates,

501
54:58.890 --> 55:03.810
then R dagger is really just R with the gates supplied
in the reverse order.

502
55:03.810 --> 55:10.020
But in general, we can always run any unitary quantum circuit in reverse in the manner that I just described,

503
55:10.020 --> 55:17.970
meaning that we apply the
gates in the reverse order and we replace each of the
individual gates by its inverse.

504
55:17.970 --> 55:24.390
If we were to do this, we'd find that first running R and then running R in
reverse does nothing at all.

505
55:24.390 --> 55:33.630
So if we started out in a standard basis state like we have here, then we would end in exactly the same standard basis state.

506
55:33.630 --> 55:41.460
Of course, doing just
that isn't very helpful, but what we can do is we can introduce a bunch of extra qubits and specifically,

507
55:41.460 --> 55:47.970
this is M qubits where M is the number of output bits of the circuit C.

508
55:47.970 --> 55:55.080
These additional qubits could
be in any quantum state, but to explain how this works, we're going to assume that they're in a standard basis state

509
55:55.080 --> 56:02.580
corresponding to some string Y. So Y is an M-bit string, and what we can do is to perform

510
56:02.580 --> 56:09.240
a bunch of controlled NOT
gates like you see right here, which effectively XORs the string F of X

511
56:09.240 --> 56:12.720
onto the string Y stored
in these bottom M qubits.

512
56:12.720 --> 56:18.900
And so the output of
the entire computation is as it appears on the screen.

513
56:18.900 --> 56:28.230
X and Y are arbitrary binary strings. X has M-bits and Y has M-bits, and we also need K workspace qubits.

514
56:28.230 --> 56:36.300
When we run R, we compute F of X and that string is stored
in the top M qubits, but we also have a
bunch of garbage qubits,

515
56:36.300 --> 56:44.910
so we XOR the output F of
X onto the bottom M qubits and then run R in reverse
to clean up the garbage.

516
56:44.910 --> 56:48.750
I should point out that it's important that R is deterministic.

517
56:48.750 --> 56:55.440
If these top M qubits could be instead in some superposition of
standard base of stats, this wouldn't work correctly,

518
56:55.440 --> 56:59.100
but this does work when
R is deterministic.

519
56:59.100 --> 57:07.800
So if we compare the quantum
circuit we just built to the original Boolean circuit C, we see that it basically
works in the same way

520
57:07.800 --> 57:12.480
that a query gate works
for an arbitrary function.

521
57:12.480 --> 57:20.340
There is a difference here, which is that we need
these workspace qubits to make it all work, but otherwise we've
effectively built a query gate

522
57:20.340 --> 57:25.680
or a query circuit for whatever function it is that C computes.

523
57:25.680 --> 57:32.220
We also managed, by the way, to return the workspace
qubits to their initial state, so they could in principle be reused

524
57:32.220 --> 57:38.010
as workspace qubits for
subsequent computations.

525
57:38.010 --> 57:47.280
If we want to, we can put a box around the entire quantum circuit and call it Q and the relationship to
C becomes more clear.

526
57:47.280 --> 57:53.637
The circuit Q will be
bigger than C in general. We need a handful of quantum
gates in Q for each gate of C,

527
57:53.637 --> 58:01.530
and we also need the controlled
NOT gates in the middle, but the number is still
linear in the size of C.

528
58:01.530 --> 58:10.710
It should also be noted that this is a completely general procedure which works for any Boolean circuit, and we haven't tried at all to optimize Q.

529
58:10.710 --> 58:17.040
For a specific circuit C, there might very well be
ways to reduce the size of Q, and that includes using methods

530
58:17.040 --> 58:24.180
that reduce the number of
workspace qubits needed in case that's something
that we want to do, and that is the procedure for running

531
58:24.180 --> 58:27.750
classical computations
on a quantum computer.

532
58:27.750 --> 58:32.850
It's pretty simple, but it's an important
thing to be able to do.

533
58:32.850 --> 58:38.850
In particular, now that
we know how to do this, we are free to make use of any classical computations we want

534
58:38.850 --> 58:48.090
inside of quantum computations, provided that we follow this form where the input gets echoed and the output gets XORed
onto a bunch of qubits

535
58:48.090 --> 58:51.540
just like we had for query gates.

536
58:51.540 --> 58:59.010
The cost scales linearly. So for example, we can
create quantum circuits for problems like integer addition,

537
58:59.010 --> 59:09.330
multiplication, division, computing GCDs and modular exponentiation, and this can all be done at the same asymptotic cost
as for Boolean circuits.

538
59:09.330 --> 59:15.540
We do need workspace qubits to do this, but at least they're available to be reused again when
we're done with them.

539
59:15.540 --> 59:21.810
One final remark that's worth mentioning is that this method provides us with a method to implement query gates,

540
59:21.810 --> 59:24.990
which I alluded to in the previous lesson.

541
59:24.990 --> 59:33.720
That is, if we have a query algorithm that takes some function F as input, and we have a way to compute
F with a Boolean circuit,

542
59:33.720 --> 59:40.650
then we can follow this procedure to build a query gate for that function and then run our query algorithm on it.

543
59:40.650 --> 59:49.110
Whether or not that's a useful thing to do depends on the query problem itself and what we're trying to accomplish, but in essence, this
construction provides us

544
59:49.110 --> 59:54.120
with a way of connecting the query model to a more standard model of computation.

545
59:54.120 --> 59:59.340
This is in some sense how Shor's algorithm for integer factorization works.

546
59:59.340 --> 60:05.550
We're going to build
quantum circuits like this out of some of the arithmetic operations we talked about earlier in the lesson.

547
60:05.550 --> 60:13.500
And by doing that, we
give quantum circuits the ability to evaluate those operations on super positions of classical states.

548
60:13.500 --> 60:18.840
And as we will see, that allows us to factor integers efficiently.

549
60:18.840 --> 60:29.130
That's the end of this lesson, which has focused mainly on establishing a foundation
for quantum algorithms in a standard non-black box
computational framework.

550
60:29.130 --> 60:35.190
We talked about computational cost mainly through the lens of problems connected with basic number theory.

551
60:35.190 --> 60:41.640
We discussed polynomial
versus exponential cost for computational tasks, and we saw how classical computations

552
60:41.640 --> 60:48.180
can be implemented by quantum circuits in a clean garbage-free manner that allows them to be used as subroutines

553
60:48.180 --> 60:51.720
inside of larger quantum computations.

554
60:51.720 --> 61:01.170
I hope you'll join me for the next lesson where we'll see how Shor's algorithm puts these ideas to use, allowing us to factorize
integers at polynomial cost.

555
61:01.170 --> 61:02.133
Goodbye until then.
